1.2 Model based on number of deaths

dthRateHp <- 0.035
lag <- 16

A quick model assumes the most reliable data is provided by the number of deaths at each date/region. Assuming a death-rate of 3.5% and a lag between the detected infection and the actual death of 16 days, for each date/region, you can derive the actual number of infected people over the total population.

\[ \text{Infected*}_{t,R} = \frac {dead_{t+lag,R}}{deathRate}\]

\[ \text{Multiplier}_{t,R} = \frac{\text{Infected*}_{t,R}}{\text{Officially Infected}_{t,R}}\] [R is the index for the Region, t is the ID of a specific date]

This can be charted as follows:

dfReg %>%
  arrange(data) %>%
  group_by(Regione) %>%
  mutate(leadDead = lead(deceduti, lag),
         hpCasi = leadDead/dthRateHp,
         hpCasiOnCasi = hpCasi/totale_casi) %>%
  filter(!is.infinite(hpCasiOnCasi), !is.na(hpCasiOnCasi), !is.nan(hpCasiOnCasi),
         data > as.Date("2020-02-27"),
         !(Regione  %in% c("Bolzano", "Trento"))) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x= data, y = hpCasiOnCasi, color = Regione)) +
  geom_line() +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Infected multiplier by date/region",
       subtitle = paste0("Death rate: ", format(dthRateHp* 100), "%, lag: ", lag, " days"),
       caption = paste("SOURCE: DPC data as of", format(maxDateTime, "%d-%h %H:%M")),
       x= "",
       y = "Multiplier")

A dataset is built1 and the results projected for the last available date.

The logical jump being applied is then to assume that the Multiplier for (t,R) is a good proxy for the multiplier as of (t+lag,R). Otherwise we would be always 16 days behind.

test <- dfReg %>%
  arrange(data) %>%
  group_by(Regione) %>%
  mutate(leadDead = lead(deceduti, lag),
         hpCasi = leadDead/dthRateHp,
         hpCasiOnCasi = hpCasi/totale_casi) %>%
  filter(!is.infinite(hpCasiOnCasi), !is.na(hpCasiOnCasi), !is.nan(hpCasiOnCasi)) %>%
  filter(data > as.Date("2020-02-27")) %>%
  ungroup()

Effectively we assume:

\[\text{Multiplier}_{max(t)} = \frac{\text{Infected*}_{max(t-lag),R}}{\text{Officially Infected}_{max(t),R}}\]

top10 <- dfReg %>%
    filter(data == max(data),
           !(Regione %in% c("Bolzano", "Trento"))) %>%
    left_join(test[test$data == max(test$data), c("Regione", "hpCasiOnCasi")], by= "Regione") %>%
    mutate(hpCasi = hpCasiOnCasi * totale_casi,
           percPopHp = hpCasi/census,
           percPop = totale_casi/census) %>%
    arrange(desc(percPopHp)) %>%
    select(Regione, deceduti, totale_casi, hpCasiOnCasi, hpCasi, census, percPopHp, percPop) %>%
    head(10) %>%
    as.data.frame()

2 Charting the death path

2.1 Tree-based model

The first model implemented is the Generalized Boosted Regression Model (GBM)

This is a black-box style algorithm which is very useful for prediction and somewhat useful for inference (returning the set of the most important variables thrown at it).

The attempt is to fit the daily change in the death number (DDead variable).

modelSet <- dfReg %>%
  select(data, ricov = ricoverati_con_sintomi, ICU = terapia_intensiva,
         homeBound = isolamento_domiciliare, currentPositives = Positivi,
         discharged = dimessi_guariti, dead = deceduti, totalInfected = totale_casi,
         tests = tamponi, Region = Regione, Pop = census, RegSize = size,
         RegAvgDens = density, MainArea = class) %>%
  mutate(MainArea = as.factor(MainArea),
         Region = as.factor(Region),
         days = as.numeric(data-min(data))) %>%
  select(-data) %>%
  arrange(days) %>%
  group_by(Region) %>%
  mutate(DDead = dead-lag(dead)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  filter(!is.na(DDead)) %>%
  select(-c(currentPositives, ricov, totalInfected, dead))

is.fact <- sapply(modelSet, is.factor)
is.num <- sapply(modelSet, is.numeric)

Variables: 2 are factors and 9 are numeric.

dependentVariable <- "DDead"

depVar <- modelSet[, dependentVariable]
num.var <- modelSet[, !(names(modelSet) %in% dependentVariable) & is.num]
fact.var <- modelSet[, is.fact]

correlation <- cor(num.var)

highCorr <- findCorrelation(correlation, cutoff = .80)
highCorrNames <- names(num.var[, highCorr])
corrplot(correlation, type= "lower", order = "hclust")

Highly correlated variables are ICU,homeBound. Ideally you would get rid of them to avoid multicollinearity. Given its tree-based model it doesnt really matter.

Transforming factors into dummy variable (with all cases - tree model)

trnsFact <- dummyVars(~., data=fact.var, fullRank = F)
factData <- predict(trnsFact, fact.var)

fullSet_pp <- cbind(factData, num.var, depVar)

Cross-validation using GBM/Caret and picking up the optimized hyper-parameters.

set.seed(1)
inTraining <- createDataPartition(fullSet_pp[, dependentVariable], p = 2/3, list = FALSE)
train <- fullSet_pp[inTraining,]
test <- fullSet_pp[-inTraining,]

Grid <-  expand.grid(shrinkage = 0.1, #seq(0.0075, 0.01, by=0.0025),
                     n.trees = seq(100, 300, by= 100),
                     n.minobsinnode = seq(1, 2, by = 1),
                     interaction.depth = seq(1, 2, by = 1))

control <- trainControl(method="cv", number=10)

rf.fit <- train(DDead ~., data = train,
                tuneGrid = Grid,
                method = "gbm",
                trControl = control,
                verbose = F)

RMSEtrn <- sqrt(mean((train[, dependentVariable]-predict(rf.fit, train))^2))
RMSEtst <- sqrt(mean((test[, dependentVariable]-predict(rf.fit, test))^2))

RMSE train: 6.1 and RMSE test: 16

show(chart)

plot(fullSet_pp[, dependentVariable], predict(gbm.fit, n.trees = gbm.fit$n.trees), 
     main = "Actual/Fitted DDead (45deg line)",
     xlab = "Actual", ylab = "Fitted")
abline(0,1, col = "red")

2.2 Lasso model

Same exercise using a more traditional regression model based on the lasso technique (shrinking the number of variables via a penalty applied to the weakest regressors). This model might have worse results, but it allows for easier inference.

x_vars <- model.matrix(DDead ~. , modelSet)
y_var <- modelSet$DDead

lambda_seq <- 10^seq(0, -1, by = -.1)

Optimizing lambda hyper-parameter.

set.seed(86)
train = sample(1:nrow(x_vars), nrow(x_vars) * 2 / 3)
test = setdiff(1:nrow(x_vars), train)

cv_output <- cv.glmnet(x_vars[train,], y_var[train], 
                       alpha = 1, lambda = lambda_seq)

s <- cv_output$lambda.min

coeff <- data.frame(
  feature=rownames(coef(cv_output, s=s))[which(coef(cv_output, s=s) != 0)],
  coeficient=coef(cv_output, s=s)[which(coef(cv_output, s=s) != 0)]
)
coeff %>%
  kable(digits = c(0,3)) %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed"), full_width = F)

2.3 Forecasting the death path two weeks forward

The output from the GBM model will be used. Two extra weeks will be added assuming the same path currently experienced for the relevant variables. Alternative paths can be considered.

2.4 Chart for selected regions

rbind(LombPrevSet, EmilPrevSet, PiemPrevSet, MarcPrevSet, LiguPrevSet, VenePrevSet) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = days, y = DDead, linetype = set)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_vline(xintercept =  max(pastData$days), color = "blue", size = 0.1) +
  facet_wrap(~Region, scales = "free_y", nrow = 2) +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_linetype_discrete("") +
  theme(legend.position="bottom")+
  labs(title = "GBM model prediction - selected regions",
       x = paste("Days since", format(min(dfReg$data), "%d-%h")),
       y = "DDead")

  1. Data for the two regions of Bolzano and Trento are excluded as very volatile and possibly outliers [this might change]

  2. The current regression model hasnt been optimized and just relies on a reasonable assumption that the number of people infected is linked to the percentage of people being tested and the broad location.
